==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scout
<hw>Scout</hw> <pr>(skout)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Icel.
<ets>sk⟦umac⟧ta</ets> a taunt; cf. Icel. <ets>sk⟦umac⟧ta</ets> to jut
out, <ets>skota</ets> to shove, <ets>skj⟦omac⟧ta</ets> to shoot, to
shove. See <er>Shoot</er>.]</ety> <def>To reject with contempt, as
something absurd; to treat with ridicule; to flout; <as>as, to
<ex>scout</ex> an idea or an apology</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Flout 'em and
<xex>scout</xex> 'em.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Scout
<hw>Scout</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>escoute</ets> scout, spy,
fr. <ets>escouter</ets>, <ets>escolter</ets>, to listen, to hear, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧couter</ets>, fr. L. <ets>auscultare</ets>, to hear with
attention, to listen to. See <er>Auscultation</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A person sent out to gain and bring in tidings; especially, one
employed in war to gain information of the movements and condition of an
enemy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Scouts</qex> each coast light-arm⟦egrave⟧d scour,⟦br⟧
Each quarter, to descry the distant foe.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A college student's or undergraduate's servant; --
so called in Oxford, England; at Cambridge called a <xex>gyp</xex>; and
at Dublin, a <xex>skip</xex>.</def> <mark>[Cant]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Cricket)</fld> <def>A fielder in a game for
practice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The act of scouting or reconnoitering.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While the rat is on the <qex>scout</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A boy scout or girl scout (which see,
above).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Scout</er>, <er>Spy</er>.</syn> -- <usage>In
a military sense a <xex>scout</xex> is a soldier who does duty in his
proper uniform, however hazardous his adventure. A <xex>spy</xex> is one
who in disguise penetrates the enemies' lines, or lurks near them, to
obtain information.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Scout
<hw>Scout</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Scouted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Scouting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To observe, watch,
or look for, as a scout; to follow for the purpose of observation, as a
scout.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Take more men,⟦br⟧
And <qex>scout</qex> him round.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pass over or through, as a scout; to reconnoiter;
<as>as, to <ex>scout</ex> a country</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Scout
<hw>Scout</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To go on the business of scouting,
or watching the motions of an enemy; to act as a scout.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With obscure wing⟦br⟧
<qex>Scout</qex> far and wide into the realm of night.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scovel</ent>⟦br⟧
